          "body": "Verses 10-11 are the theological center of the psalm and one of the most compressed and radical statements in the Psalter about divine values. The horse represented the highest military technology of the ancient world; the 'legs of a man' (*shoq*) refers to the infantry warrior's physical power. Both are explicitly named as things in which the LORD takes no delight and no pleasure. This is not pacifism — it is a statement about what the LORD evaluates. Psalm 20:7 makes the same contrast: 'Some boast in chariots and some in horses, but we will boast in the name of the LORD our God.' The post-exilic community, rebuilding without chariots, was tempted to envy the surrounding nations' military strength. The psalm tells them: you are building with the wrong metric. The LORD's metric is *yir'ah* (fear — reverent awe that produces obedience) and *yachal* (waiting, hoping — active trust in the *chesed* He has promised). Those are the ones He favors. The psalm does not promise the fearful will be strongest; it promises they will be favored."
